         <abstract id="aspace_a68ed7c57f80d9e797670c0333f98581">This collection draws together mostly printed documentation relating to mission agencies and World Christian churches. It complements other substantial archival collections held by the Divinity Library.</abstract>
         <origination label="Creator">
            <corpname source="local">
               <part localtype="agent_corporate_entity">Yale University. Divinity School. Library</part>
            </corpname>
         </origination>
      </did>
      <bioghist id="aspace_642af3dfdf34cf24bef6aaae88d0c0c6">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The modern Protestant missionary movement dates to 1792 when William Carey was instrumental in founding the Baptist Missionary Society in England and went to India as a missionary, landing in Calcutta [Kolkata] in November of 1793. Catholic missionaries were sent around the world well before this. Various Protestant denominations as well as independent agencies established missionary societies beginning in the 19th century and over time independent indigenous churches and mission agencies arose in the areas where missionaries had served.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_60bd909fc15a56b16e67e9a3cde90ccf">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The collection is open for research.</p>
      </accessrestrict>
      <arrangement id="aspace_6cea06c0fc54e798555270f788213216">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The collection is organized geographically:</p>
         <p>Series I: Africa</p>
         <p>Series II: Asia</p>
         <p>Series III: Europe and the United Kingdom</p>
         <p>Series IV: Latin America and the Caribbean</p>
         <p>Series V: Middle East</p>
         <p>Series VI: North America</p>
         <p>Series VII: Oceania</p>
      </arrangement>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_45d6498dc73c019b8770de4e56faa32e">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>Much of this collection consists of printed or mimeographed reports, memos, brochures and other documentation of the work of the Western mission agencies and the indigenous churches and organizations that arose out of the missionary movement. This material came to the Divinity Library in various ways over the years. The documentation in this collection is not comprehensive but it provides useful background and detail about mission agencies and Christian organizations in the areas served by missionaries. The majority of the material in this collection dates from the 19th and 20th centuries.</p>
         <p>The organizations included in this collection have been filed according to the geographical location of their administrative headquarters, which in many cases differed from their geographical areas of service. This collection excludes materials that were included in Yale Divinity Library Record Group 342, Records of Ecumenical Work for Coordination and Documentation of Missions and World Christianity, and Record Group 347, Records of Mission and World Christian Educational and Medical Institutions and Organizations.</p>
         <p>This collection includes materials that were formerly cataloged by the Library with HR call numbers, standing for "Historical Records."</p>
      </scopecontent>
